ce:section.ce:para:
For investigating the practical application of this proposed method, standard recovery experiments were accordingly performed using drug samples (Table 2
                        ) and milk samples (Table 3
                        ). Before determination, drug samples were diluted by ultrapure water to an appropriate concentration (500nM), and the milk samples were supplemented with various amounts of OTC. All of the samples were directly determined by this fluorescent strategy. The OTC contents in all samples were derived from standard curves and regression equations. Importantly, as listed in Table 2 and Table 3, the recovery of the proposed method was in the range of 96.9%-104.2%, indicating the proposed sensing platform may broaden ways for practically detecting OTC in real samples. As shown in Fig. S12, the fluorescence spectrum of CDs apparently decreases with the increased concentration of OTC tablets samples, which is just the same with those standard OTC samples. Furthermore, in the concentration range of 25 nM-1.75μM, a linear relationship was also found between ΔF and the concentration of OTC tablets samples. The linear regression equation is ΔF=0.0452+0.1577*c, R2
                        =0.99024, where ΔF and c have the same meanings as above. It is found that the slope and the intercept of the linear regression equations of standard OTC samples and OTC tablets samples are almost equivalent, which suggests that the OTC tablets matrix does not interfere the assay of OTC.
